entity.description: A longtime favorite of children and adults, and a staple of PBS, "Sesame Street" bridges many cultural and educational gaps with a fun program. @asinghtoo if you have the symptoms, ask a doctor to be checked out for sleep apnea. first it’s a questionnaire, then if they think it’s a possibility, you stay overnight in a ‘sleep study’ where they track your breathing/heart rate etc and potentially prescribe you a device. super easy!!

In the 4 years since dad had his main stroke/coma, not one doc mentioned apneas. It took a passing comment, brain scans, noticing more strokes over time, several nights with a baby monitor and a lot of stress. read up on sleep apnea. if you’re at all unsure, plz ask for a test ❤️

text: sleep study showed my dad has very severe sleep apnea. hundreds of episodes per hour of sleep, including 1-2min periods where he didn’t breathe at all (!) he could have died in his sleep anytime. this has caused several small strokes over the years, tiredness and depression

docs reckon > 22 million Americans have moderate to severe obstructive sleep apnea with > 80% undiagnosed. had a family member ever die in their sleep? could have been sleep apnea.  strokes? could have been caused by sleep apneas. this shit is lethal

text: @PaulRoales in Palo Alto, 4 hours.
@AndySwan maybe that’s what I should do this weekend

there’s an entire cottage industry that preys on vulnerable older people. the bar to building good products here is much lower than you think. and for people who want to keep their parents at home, we’ll pay almost anything.

a special market target - high earning non-us citizens who permanently reside here but can’t claim dependencies on their taxes nor get their parents insurance when they’re here. to put in context, visiting home care for us can be $600 *a day* and it’s shoddy.

the whole area of senior care needs to be disrupted. this is a request for a gazillion products. i spend ~50% of my monthly income caring for my parents, and almost every service is below par or just a scam. there’s a huge opportunity to be leveraged here.

a reason to think that is also because socially conservative people (similar by-products) often signal as happier than their counterparts within the same country

@evankimbrell not talking about things like poverty, health etc... the world is amazing and getting better for sure (though could be faster)... but that’s not correlating with societal/individual happiness.. the chasm between progress and happiness is what I’m seemingly failing to highlight 🙃

@richmcateer The last point is, I realized recently, the crux of The Fountainhead. Roark tells Dominique he’ll wait for her to one day realize that there is no way the world can destroy them. There’s a deep point there which I think I’m only just starting to comprehend (@cryptoseneca)

@richmcateer yes 100% that’s part of the meaning, but I think people presuppose deliberate dishonesty with the word ‘scam’. Sometimes misaligned incentives can be the natural result of complex systems or simply be an observation issue- there was a naïveté that missed the performative aspect
really it’s meant to be a funny and inelegant version of Dagny and Galt’s comment ‘we never had to take any of it seriously, did we?’ (which is a much more loaded sentence in context of the book)

some people get confused over the ‘everything’s a scam’ line. it’s less about the dictionary definition of ‘scam’ and more that most things are performative. for *some* people, becoming aware of the different reality theater productions is the key to their self-efficacy
